C: Iron Fist Cast Makes First-Ever Live Appearance |last=Damore |first=Meagan |date=October 8, 2016 |website=[[Comic Book Resources]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161009182639/http://www.cbr.com/nycc-iron-fist-cast-makes-first-ever-live-appearance/ |archive-date=October 9, 2016 |access-date=October 9, 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"DawsonDefenders\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.comingsoon.net/tv/news/782357-scott-glenn-rachael-taylor-and-rosario-dawson-confirmed-for-the-defenders#/slide/1 |title=Scott Glenn, Rachael Taylor, and Rosario Dawson Confirmed for The Defenders |last=Perry |first=Spencer |date=November 2, 2016 |website=[[ComingSoon.net]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161103142719/http://www.comingsoon.net/tv/news/782357-scott-glenn-rachael-taylor-and-rosario-dawson-confirmed-for-the-defenders#/slide/1 |archive-date=November 3, 2016 |access-date=November 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"NNLC\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.indiewire.com/2016/10/luke-cage-back-to-the-future-stan-lee-easter-eggs-1201733058/ |title=\u2018Luke Cage\u2019 Easter Eggs: Stan Lee, Iron Man and More |last=Nguyen |first=Hanh |date=October 4, 2016 |website=[[IndieWire]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161110162044/http://www.indiewire.com/2016/10/luke-cage-back-to-the-future-stan-lee-easter-eggs-1201733058/ |archive-date=November 10, 2016 |access-date=November 15, 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"DawsonNoPunisher\">{{Cite web |url=http://collider.com/rosario-dawson-unforgettable-the-defenders-interview/ |title=Rosario Dawson on \u2018Unforgettable\u2019 and the Revenge of the Ex |last=Radish |first=Christina |date=April 21, 2017 |website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424174412/http://collider.com/rosario-dawson-unforgettable-the-defenders-interview/ |archive-date=April 24, 2017 |access-date=April 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"DawsonFuture\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.screengeek.net/2018/05/28/rosario-dawson-marvel-tv-future/ |title=Rosario Dawson May Be Done With Marvel TV After \u2018Luke Cage\u2019 Season 2 |last=Hadden |first=James |date=May 28, 2018 |website=Screen Geek |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180528235819/https://www.screengeek.net/2018/05/28/rosario-dawson-marvel-tv-future/ |archive-date=May 28, 2018 |access-date=May 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"DawsonLastScene\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2018/09/rosario-dawson-marvel-netflix-claire-luke-cage-final-scene-1202007010/ |title=Rosario Dawson May Be Done With the Marvel Universe, and Helped Write Her Final Scene on \u2018Luke Cage\u2019 |last=Shannon Miller |first=Liz |date=September 25, 2018 |website=[[IndieWire]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181007145510/https://www.indiewire.com/2018/09/rosario-dawson-marvel-netflix-claire-luke-cage-final-scene-1202007010/ |archive-date=October 7, 2018 |access-date=October 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n{{Marvel Cinematic Universe|selected=Cast}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Temple, Claire}}\n[[Category:Characters created by Drew Goddard]]\n[[Category:Female characters in television]]\n[[Category:Television characters introduced in 2015]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters from New York City]]\n[[Category:Fictional African-American people]]\n[[Category:Fictional American nurses]]\n[[Category:Fictional female medical personnel]]\n[[Category:Fictional Hispanic and Latino American people]]\n[[Category:Marvel Cinematic Universe characters]]\n[[Category:Marvel Comics television characters]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox character\n| color              = #AF181F\n| name               = Claire Temple\n| series             = {{no italics|[[Marvel Cinematic Universe]]}}\n| image              = Claire Temple MCU.png\n| caption            = Rosario Dawson as Claire Temple in ''Daredevil''\n| based_on           = [[Claire Temple]]\n| first              = \"[[Cut Man (Daredevil)|Cut Man]]\" (2015) <br /> (''[[Daredevil (TV series)|Daredevil]]'')\n| last               = \"[[Wig Out (Luke Cage)|Wig Out]]\" (2018) <br /> (''[[Luke Cage (TV series)|Luke Cage]]'')\n| creator            = {{plainlist|\n*[[Archie Goodwin (comics)|Archie Goodwin]]\n*[[George Tuska]]}}\n| adapted_by         = [[Drew Goddard]]\n| portrayer          = [[Rosario Dawson]]\n| occupation         = Nurse\n| family             = Soledad Temple (mother)\n| nationality        = American\n}}\n'''Claire Temple''' is a [[character (arts)|character]] portrayed by [[Rosario Dawson]] in the television series of the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]] (MCU), based on the [[Marvel Comics]] characters [[Claire Temple]] and [[Night Nurse (comics)|Night Nurse]]. A nurse who gives medical aid to vigilantes, she was created for the [[Daredevil (season 1)|first season]] of ''[[Daredevil (TV series)|Daredevil]]'' (2015). Dawson then signed a deal to return for the [[Daredevil (season 2)|second season]] of the series (2016), as well as potentially appear in any other [[List of Marvel Cinematic Universe television series#Netflix series|Marvel Netflix series]]. She has since reprised the role in ''[[Jessica Jones (TV series)|Jessica Jones]]'' (2015), ''[[Luke Cage (TV series)|Luke Cage]]'' (2016\u20132018), ''[[Iron Fist (TV series)|Iron Fist]]'' (2017\u20132018), and ''[[The Defenders (miniseries)|The Defenders]]'' (2017). The character has also appeared in a [[Marvel Cinematic Universe tie-in comics#Marvel's Jessica Jones (2015)|''Jessica Jones'' tie-in comic]] (2015).\n\n== Marvel Cinematic Universe ==\n=== Television series ===\n{{further|Daredevil (TV series)|Jessica Jones (TV series)|Luke Cage (TV series)|Iron Fist (TV series)|The Defenders (miniseries)}}\nAfter discovering [[Daredevil (Marvel Comics character)|Matt Murdock / Daredevil]] beaten in a dumpster in ''Daredevil'', nurse Claire Temple gives him aid.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Cut Man |episode-link=Cut Man (Daredevil) |series=Marvel's Daredevil |network=[[Netflix]] |date=April 10, 2015 |season=1 |number=2 |credits=Abraham, Phil (director); Drew Goddard (writer)}}</ref> She is kidnapped by the mafia for this, as bait for Daredevil, and though he is able to save her,<ref>{{Cite episode |title=In the Blood |episode-link=In the Blood (Daredevil) |series=Marvel's Daredevil |network=[[Netflix]] |date=April 10, 2015 |season=1 |number=4 |credits=Girotti, Ken (director); Joe Pokaski (writer)}}</ref> they mutually decide that it is too dangerous to become involved, in spite of the spark between them. Claire does continue to give him medical aid as needed, while Murdock occasionally uses her position at Metro-General Hospital to his advantage.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=The Path of the Righteous |episode-link=The Path of the Righteous |series=Marvel's Daredevil |network=[[Netflix]] |date=April 10, 2015 |season=1 |number=11 |credits=Gomez, Nick (director); Steven S. DeKnight and Douglas Petrie (writer)}}</ref>\n\nIn ''Jessica Jones'', Temple is on duty at the hospital when a seriously injured [[Luke Cage]] is brought in; Temple takes care of Cage for [[Jessica Jones]].<ref>{{Cite episode |title=AKA Smile |episode-link=AKA Smile |series=Marvel's Jessica Jones |network=[[Netflix]] |date=November 20, 2015 |season=1 |number=13 |credits=Rymer, Michael (director); Scott Reynolds & Melissa Rosenberg (story); Jamie King & Scott Reynolds (writer)}}</ref> In the [[Daredevil (season 2)|second season of ''Daredevil'']], Temple quits her job at the hospital, when it tries to cover up the death of her coworker following an attack by [[The Hand (comics)|The Hand]], and leaves [[Hell's Kitchen, Manhattan|Hell's Kitchen]];<ref>{{Cite episode |title=.380 |episode-link=.380 (Daredevil) |series=Marvel's Daredevil |network=[[Netflix]] |date=March 18, 2016 |season=2 |number=11 |credits=Surjik, Stephen (director); Mark Verheiden (writer)}}</ref> she arrives in [[Harlem]], where her mother runs a diner, in ''Luke Cage''. Temple reconnects with Cage there, and helps him defend the neighborhood.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Just to Get a Rep |episode-link=Just to Get a Rep (Luke Cage) |series=Marvel's Luke Cage |network=[[Netflix]] |date=September 30, 2016 |season=1 |number=5 |credits=Jobst, Marc (director); Jason Horwitch (writer)}}</ref> She falls for Cage, but before they can act on their feelings he is arrested.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=You Know My Steez |episode-link=You Know My Steez (Luke Cage) |series=Marvel's Luke Cage |network=[[Netflix]] |date=September 30, 2016 |season=1 |number=13 |credits=Johnson, Clark (director); Aida Mashaka Croal & Cheo Hodari Coker (writer)}}</ref>\n\nTemple begins taking lessons at [[Colleen Wing]]'s dojo, through whom she meets [[Iron Fist (comics)|Danny Rand]] in ''Iron Fist''.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Under Leaf Pluck Lotus |episode-link=Under Leaf Pluck Lotus |series=Marvel's Iron Fist |network=[[Netflix]] |date=March 17, 2017 |season=1 |number=5 |credits=Briesewitz, Uta (director); Cristine Chambers (writer)}}</ref> Temple helps Rand in his fight against The Hand.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Dragon Plays with Fire |episode-link=Dragon Plays with Fire |series=Marvel's Iron Fist |network=[[Netflix]] |date=March 17, 2017 |season=1 |number=13 |credits=Surjik, Stephen (director); Scott Buck, Tamara Becher-Wilkinson and Pat Charles (writer)}}</ref> In ''The Defenders'', Temple is reunited with Cage, who is let out of jail early thanks to Foggy Nelson, and resumes a relationship with him.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=The H Word |episode-link=The H Word |series=The Defenders |network=[[Netflix]] |date=August 18, 2017 |season=1 |number=1 |credits=Clarkson, S.J. (director); Douglas Petrie & Marco Ramirez (writer)}}</ref> She then introduces Cage to Rand.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Worst Behavior |episode-link=Worst Behavior (The Defenders) |series=The Defenders |network=[[Netflix]] |date=August 18, 2017 |season=1 |number=3 |credits=Hoar, Peter (director); Lauren Schmidt Hissrich & Douglas Petrie (writer)}}</ref>\n\nIn the second season of ''Luke Cage'', Temple continues her relationship with Cage, but suddenly grows cautious of his personal issues, particularly with his father and the way he handles justice.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Straighten It Out |episode-link=Straighten It Out (Luke Cage) |series=Marvel's Luke Cage |network=[[Netflix]] |date=June 22, 2018 |season=2 |number=2 |credits=Green, Steph (director); Akela Cooper (writer)}}</ref> After an argument, Temple asks that they \"take a break\" from each other.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Wig Out |episode-link=Wig Out (Luke Cage) |series=Marvel's Luke Cage |network=[[Netflix]] |date=June 22, 2018 |season=2 |number=3 |credits=Jobst, Marc (director); Matt Owens (writer)}}</ref> By the end of the season, Cage has completely moved on from Temple who tries to enter Harlem's Paradise to see him, but is turned away.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=They Reminisce Over You |episode-link=They Reminisce Over You (Luke Cage) |series=Marvel's Luke Cage |network=[[Netflix]] |date=June 22, 2018 |season=2 |number=13 |credits=Lopez, Alex Garcia (director); Cheo Hodari Coker (writer)}}</ref>\n\n=== Tie-in comic ===\n{{further|Marvel Cinematic Universe tie-in comics}}\nTemple appears in the ''Jessica Jones'' tie-in comic, serving as [[Turk Barrett]]'s nurse.\n\n== Concept and creation ==\n[[Rosario Dawson]] joined the cast of ''Daredevil'' in June 2014,<ref name=\"DawsonCast\" /> and her role was revealed to be that of Temple in October of that year.<ref name=\"NYCC2014\" /> The MCU character is an amalgam of the comic characters [[Claire Temple]] and [[Night Nurse (comics)|Night Nurse]],<ref name=\"DawsonTime\" /> with ''Daredevil'' [[showrunner]] [[Steven S. DeKnight]] noting that the character was originally \"going to be the actual Night Nurse from the comics ... we had her name in a script and it came back that it was possible <nowiki>[</nowiki>[[Marvel Studios|the feature side]]<nowiki>]</nowiki> were going to use her\" and \"had plans for her down the road,\" necessitating the change to using the more obscure comics character Claire Temple as her name.<ref name=\"DeKnightNightNurse\" />\n\n{{Quote box|quote=We wanted to have an opportunity to be able to let the audience know that this person knows this person, and that means they know that person. I think if you play the game out, you can sort of see ... how important that character's going to be.|source=\u2014Jeph Loeb on Temple appearing across multiple Marvel/Netflix series<ref name=\"TempleLC\" />|width=33%|align=right}}\nIn May 2015, Dawson signed with Marvel to return for the second season of ''Daredevil'' as part of an \"exclusive TV deal\" that also allows her to appear in any other [[List of Marvel Cinematic Universe television series#Netflix series|Marvel/Netflix series]].<ref name=\"DawsonDeal\" /> Dawson explained that she signs on with Marvel for a year at a time, for a certain number of episodes, and finds out which series the episodes are for closer to the time of filming.<ref name=\"DawsonExplain\" /> In July, ''Jessica Jones'' showrunner [[Melissa Rosenberg]] revealed that Dawson would be \"dropping in\",<ref name=\"DawsonJJ\" /> with Dawson making a guest appearance in the [[Jessica Jones (season 1)#ep13|season finale]].<ref name=\"TempleLC\" /> Before ''Jessica Jones'' debuted that November, a tie-in comic prequel was released featuring several ''Daredevil'' and ''Jessica Jones'' characters, including Temple, to explore \"the connective tissue that will build between the series\".<ref name=\"JJOneShot\" /><ref name=\"JJOneShotTemple\" />\n\nMarvel announced in September 2015 that Dawson would be appearing in ''Luke Cage'',<ref name=\"DawsonLC\" /> in what Cage actor [[Mike Colter]] described as a \"significant part\", noting that the comics character Claire Temple was introduced as a love interest for Cage. The series introduces Temple's mother (portrayed by [[S\u00f4nia Braga]]), and gives Claire \"a large storyline ... [she helps] out a lot.\"<ref name=\"TempleLC\" /> It also references her role as a version of Night Nurse, with [[Sean Ringgold]]'s character Sugar dismissively referring to her as \"the night nurse\".<ref name=\"NNLC\" /> Explaining the decision to have Temple appear across multiple series, which has been compared to the role that [[Nick Fury (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Nick Fury]] plays as \"the connective thread\" between the [[List of Marvel Cinematic Universe films|MCU films]],<ref name=\"NickFuryMTV\" /><ref name=\"NickFuryCB\" /> Marvel Television head [[Jeph Loeb]] explained that it was due to Dawson's performance, saying \"It wasn't just that Claire fit so well in those worlds, it's that Rosario fit so well in those worlds.\"<ref name=\"TempleLC\" /> When Temple first appears in the second season of ''Daredevil'', she has \"a cut in her eyebrow\", which Daredevil actor [[Charlie Cox]] explained was from one of the other series, saying that \"the timeline had been thought through and worked out\" to connect Dawson's various performances.<ref name=\"DawsonExplain\" />\n\nIn July 2016, Dawson was unable to promote ''Luke Cage'' because she was \"back in New York ... filming something else for Marvel TV\",<ref name=\"DawsonIF?\" /> which was confirmed that October to be ''[[Iron Fist (TV series)|Iron Fist]]''; this appearance was set up at the end of ''Luke Cage''.<ref name=\"DawsonIF\" /> A month later, Dawson was revealed to also be reprising her role in the crossover miniseries ''[[The Defenders (miniseries)|The Defenders]]''.<ref name=\"DawsonDefenders\" /> Dawson also expressed interest in making a [[cameo appearance]] in ''[[The Punisher (TV series)|The Punisher]]'', a spin-off series from ''Daredevil'', but was unable to due to a scheduling conflict.<ref name=\"DawsonNoPunisher\" />\n\n{{Quote box|quote=I wanted it to really honor this journey I\u2019ve had with her, and what she\u2019s been and what she\u2019s stood for, and what she means to a lot of people ... because [she shows that] you don\u2019t have to have special superpowers to make a difference and an impact in your community and to challenge yourself to grow and to be greater. She just really inspired me a lot.|source=Rosario Dawson on her final scene portraying Temple in the second season of ''Luke Cage''<ref name=\"DawsonLastScene\" />|width=33%|align=left}}\nAfter appearing in the [[Luke Cage (season 2)|second season]] of ''Luke Cage'', Dawson explained that she was reluctant to continue making appearances in the many series due to having to travel away from her family when working on the New York sets. She did think that she would return to ''Luke Cage'' if it was renewed for further seasons, and again expressed interest in appearing in ''The Punisher'' at some point moving forward \"just so I can feel like I\u2019ve done every show\".<ref name=\"DawsonFuture\" /> Dawson later revealed that she had asked ''Luke Cage'' showrunner [[Cheo Hodari Coker]] whether she could contribute to the writing of Temple's last scene in the season; she considered the scene to be the culmination of three years of work for her, and felt that it had initially been written too much from the perspective of Cage, whom Temple has a fight with in the scene that ends their relationship. Dawson praised Coker for allowing her to push the scene to feature more of an equal balance between the characters, and Coker praised the work she did on this.<ref name=\"DawsonLastScene\" />\n\n== Characterization ==\nDawson said in April 2015, \"she\u2019s someone who also throws herself into the fray and had made it her life mission to help, even if that means risking her own life ... My character is a stand-in for the audience. She\u2019s not a love interest\u2014she\u2019s this skeptical eye looking at this strange situation.\" On the relationship between Temple and Murdock in ''Daredevil'', Dawson said, \"The show explores how necessary it is for two people to finally have their masks off with each other. For Matt Murdock, this is the first person he has that\u2019s going to be able to see that transition for him ... But she gets confronted with the question: How far will you go? What does it mean if you\u2019re helping someone who is maybe going to hurt other people?\"<ref name=\"DawsonTime\" />\n\nDawson felt that the character resonated with audiences, and was brought back for more series, because, \"She's funny, she's wry, she's strong\u2014she's built for that world, because she's great under pressure. She's someone\u2014hero or not\u2014you'd want to have in a dire situation... I really just liked her arc all the way through.\" After the character is shown using fighting in ''Daredevil'', Dawson explained, \"her eyes have been opened up to this other world\u2014and she's crossed the line. You know, this is someone who helps people, and she's been violent now but seeing the need for it. I think there's a lot that she's having to grapple with\".<ref name=\"DawsonMTV\" /> Discussing Temple's relationship with Cage in ''Luke Cage'', Colter said that \"she will deal with me in a different way than she dealt with Matt Murdock. Matt Murdock's character's completely different from mine. Because she plays a nurse that basically seems to be in the right place at the right time, and she's very good at helping out superheroes who are in need ... I think she's going to be a very good companion for Luke. I think she's someone that Luke needs in his life at this time.\"<ref name=\"TempleLC\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"DawsonCast\">{{Cite web |url=http://marvel.com/news/tv/2014/6/20/22725/rosario_dawson_joins_marvels_daredevil_for_netflix |title=Rosario Dawson Joins Marvel's Daredevil For Netflix |date=June 20, 2014 |website=[[Marvel Comics|Marvel.com]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140905195945/http://marvel.com/news/t